ency_in_corpus":867,"cross_references":{"qac":{"found":false},"wiktextract":{"found":true,"entry_count":5,"pos_tags":["adj","noun","verb"],"has_etymology":true,"sense_count":10},"lanes":{"found":true,"entry_ids":["n6011","n6018","n6019","n6020"]}},"translations":null,"definition":{"source":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"adj","gloss":"great"},{"pos":"adj","gloss":"bulky"},{"pos":"adj","gloss":"outstanding"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"the bulk (of), the majority (of); the lion's share","tags":["construct"],"examples":[{"text":"مَا لَا يُدْرَكُ كُلُّهُ، لَا يُتْرَكُ جُلُّهُ.","english":"What is not wholly achieved is not to be largely abandoned."},{"text":"جل الناسِ أعداءُ على السرَّاءِ والضَّرَّا\nفلا يغرُرْكَ مبتسمٌ وإن أبدى لكَ البشرا\nففي الصدر حزازاتٌ تكادُ تمزقُ الصدرا\nولو كادوا النجومَ هوتْ من الخضراءِ للغبرا\nوما الدنيا إذا فكر تَ غير جهنمَ الصُّغرى\nألستَ ترى بها أمماً وكلٌّ تلعنُ الأخرى\nلقد جرَّبْتُ جُلَّهُمُ فلمْ أر فيهمُ خيرا","english":"Most men are rabid foes, / Be they in joy or woe!\nDo not be fooled by smiles, / Even if seeming kind:\nIn their breasts is hateful fury, / almost tearing their hearts apart!\nIf men could plot against the stars, / The stars would fall into the mire.\nLife, if you reflect, / Is but a \"lesser Hell\":\nDo you not see in it many nations? / And each of them execrates the other!\nI have appraised most sorts and kinds, / And in all, I saw no goodness!"}]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to be illustrious"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to be beyond or above"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to be exalted or dignified"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to grow old"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"jasmine, rose","tags":["uncommon"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"horse-covering, saddlecloth","tags":["regional","uncommon"],"examples":[{"text":"ومن السوس: الأُتْرُجُّ ودُهن البنفسج والشاه سبرم والجِلال والبراذع.","english":"From Sūs one gets citrons, violet-oil, basil, and horse-covers and pack-saddles."},{"text":"وقد لبسوا التلاليس وجِلال الدوابّ وجعلوا فوق رءوسهم التراب والتبن.","english":"They were clothed in sacks and pelts of domestic beasts and had their heads covered with earth and straw."}]}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"Compare Hebrew גַּל (gall).\n\nBorrowed from Classical Persian گُل (gul). Doublet of وَرْد (ward).\n\nBorrowed from Iranian. Compare Central Kurdish جِل (cil, “beggar’s clothes”), Classical Persian جُلّ (jull, “horse-covering, saddle-cloth”), Balti [script needed] (jol, “horse cover”), Yaghnobi [script needed] (jul, “horse-cloth”), Gurani [script needed] (jal, jul, “cover, cloth”). Doublet of شَلَّاق (šallāq), جُوَالَق (juwālaq), and جُوَال (juwāl)."},"ipa":["/d͡ʒall/","/d͡ʒull/","/d͡ʒal.la/"]}